<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A species of the northern Chaco growing in somewhat degraded bushland in Bolivia and the extreme north of Paraguay.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">PARAGUAY. Alto Paraguay</emphasis>
: 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Madrejón">Madrejon</normalizedToken>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">F. Mereles</emphasis>
6696 (FCQ). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Boquerón">Boqueron</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
: Fortin Platanillos 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">F. Mereles &amp; R. Degen 6193</emphasis>
(CTES).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BOLIVIA. Santa Cruz</emphasis>
: Cordillera, P.N. Kaa-Iya, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. Fuentes &amp; G. Navarro</emphasis>
2319 (CTES, MO, NY, USZ).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mucronifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea mucronifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pseudocalystegia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea pseudocalystegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its palmately-lobed, softly hirsute, strongly mucronate leaves, combined with the lanceolate, acuminate sepals. It differs in the smaller, more deeply divided, less silvery leaves, the inflorescence of several-flowered cymes and the shorter deciduous bracteoles (up to 7 mm long, not&gt; 20 mm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
